<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-369-052  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 369 052  OV: 08 368 994.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 23 1990 v7 n16 p84(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ESCO Systems Inc. Skyscan D-120. (Hardware Review) (one of eightevaluations of hand-held scanning systems in 'Hand-held scannersfit for certain tasks.') (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Halliday, Caroline; Damore, Kelley.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>ESCO Systems Inc's $499 SkyScan D-120 hand-held scanner uses'Contact Image Sensor' technology instead of charge-coupleddevices to scan text and graphics.andP;  The product's opticalcharacter recognition accuracy is comparable to that of competingscanners.andP;  It produces graphics images with smoother curves thanother scanners, but its straight lines are more jagged.andP;  TheSkyScan is easy to roll straight, but there is no window forchecking the scanner alignment.andP;  It also suffers from problemswith merging text.andP;  Buyers say the SkyScan performs small-scaletasks, such as scanning signature cards and file folder tabs,effectively but is not suitable for use with full-size documents.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   ESCO Systems Inc. (products).andO;Product:   ESCO Skyscan D-120 (Scanning device).andO;Topic:     ScanningGraphics SystemsEvaluation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>ESCO Systems Inc.andM;SKYSCAN D-120andM;Unlike the other scanners reviewed, which use charge-coupled devices to scan,the SkyScan D-120 uses Contact Image Sensor technology.andP;  While its ICR rateswere comparable to the those of other scanners, the SkyScan produced graphicsimages with jagged, straight lines and smooth curves.andP;  (The other scannersproduced clean, straight lines but fuzzy curves.)andP;  Despite these differences,the overall quality of the images scanned was the same with all of thescanners.andM;With two long rollers on the base, the SkyScan D-120 is easy to rollstraight.andP;  However, the unit does not have a window that the buyer can use tocheck the scanner's alignment.andP;  The scan button must be held throughout thescan.andP;  The protective window on the unit's base is recessed in such a waythat it occasionally catches the top edge of the paper being scanned.andP;  Also,the scanner emits a high-pitched whistle when the scanner is active.andP;  Thoughit is not loud, the whistle is annoying.andM;Like all of the other OCR programs tested, problems with merging text wereencountered.andM;ESCO Systems Inc., of Sunnyvale, Calif., can be reached at (408) 744-9001.andM;Buyers say ...andM;Bruce Zeuli, operations manager for Micro Images Inc, a San Franciscoimage-scanning service for the legal community, uses the SkyScan D-120 toscan file-folder tabs and signature cards.andM;&quot;For what it does, it does it well,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;But if you are scanning [adocument] that is 8-1/2 by 11 inches, it is typically more trouble than it isworth.&quot;andM;For example, he explained, &quot;If you are using the OCR CAT Reader software tomerge text, you have to line up the [two files] exactly.andP;  However, it isdifficult to begin and end [scanning] at the same spot.andM;&quot;The [OCR] software is not as finished as it could be,&quot; Zeuli added.andP;  &quot;Thecommands do not seem logical.andP;  Furthermore, the [CAT Reader] does not savethe parameters programmed.andP;  It always defaults to the old ones.andP;  You have toset them up every time you move to a new page.&quot;andM;On Zeuli's wish list is a mechanism that would caliberate the speed of thescanner.andP;  &quot;When you scan too fast the image gets smaller,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;Youneed feedback to tell if you are moving too fast.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>